	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Côte d’Ivoire cocoa export ban continues</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 April 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 23 January, the internationally recognised President of Côte d’Ivoire, Alassane Ouattara, announced a one-month ban on cocoa exports as a means of increasing pressure on former president Laurent Gbagbo, who refuses to leave office despite losing the presidential elections in November 2010. In an interview with the <i>Financial Times</i>&nbsp;on 13 February, Mr Ouattara said ‘that he was committed to continue using economic sanctions to force his opponent out from office.’</p><p>Côte d’Ivoire is the world’s largest exporter of cocoa, with about 40% of global market share (i.e. 1.2 million tonnes exported in 2010), valued at US$4.5bn annually. Cocoa exports are heavily taxed in Côte d’Ivoire and constitute an important source of government revenue – meaning that any measures which can cause budget cuts are likely to trigger unrest among those civil servants and the military that remain loyal to Mr Gbagbo.</p><p>By mid February, market prices had risen by almost 10% since the ban, and fears of a possible extension helped push cocoa futures to new highs. At the same time, international cocoa traders slowed or even stopped purchasing cocoa in Côte d’Ivoire, because of declining warehouse storage capacity at the ports of Abidjan and San Pedro. Press reports note that less purchasing by corporate buyers has translated into a lower turnover for about 800,000 domestic cocoa farmers – and farmers remain particularly anxious about the potential impacts of the ban on the next midcrop starting in late March/early April, given the expected bumper crop.</p><p>Meanwhile, middle men have been using the ban to undercut recommended farm-gate prices by as much as 50%. Farmers have been selling at these reduced prices rather than risk being left with a spoilt crop and debts incurred as a result of high input costs. Unnamed officials at the international cocoa company have told reporters that ‘cocoa continues to leave the country via established smuggling routes to the east in Ghana and northwards to Burkina Faso.’</p><p>On 14 March, Malick Tohe, an advisor to presidential claimant Ouattara, said in an interview with Bloomberg that ‘the ban has been extended until March 31’. Laurent Gbagbo has in turn threatened to nationalise the cocoa sector, which diplomats are reported to see as ‘a desperate attempt’ to mobilise the financial resources required to pay the military and civil servants. In fact, the Gbagbo-controlled cocoa authority in the country has already warned exporters that they should ship their cocoa beans until the end of March and pay the appropriate taxes, or risk their stocks being seized. Warehouses near Abidjan are estimated variously to hold between 440,000 and 475,000 tonnes of cocoa.</p>
		
		
