				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>It was feared that, with an extension of the cocoa export ban, supplies would tighten further and drive market prices even higher. However, the taking of the main export port by Ouattara’s forces at the end of March led to the first fall in cocoa futures prices for over two months. In response, EU officials commented that there were no current plans to lift sanctions, which would take 4-5 days to lift when the timing was judged to be right.</p><p>Great concerns exist among the world’s largest cocoa traders, including Cargill, Archer Daniels Midland, Barry Callebaut, Olam, and Armajaro, and local farming communities. While traders have been concerned about limited cocoa storage capacity and potential losses caused by the deterioration of product quality, farmers feared that they would not be able sell their cocoa in this bumper crop year. Cocoa farmers’ leaders have complained that the economic burden of the ban is being unevenly spread along the supply chain, with farmers bearing the principal burden, while middlemen and traders cash in.</p><p>However the middlemen and traders, having bought up the cocoa crop, are now themselves caught up in the political impasse. The opposing parties’ differing pronouncements for the cocoa sector have left traders in the unenviable situation of effectively being told to choose sides, one demanding that they export and the other demanding that they halt exports and respect sanctions, with the threat of losing their whole crop or their livelihoods in the short or long run.</p><p>The heightened climate of violence and worsening humanitarian situation make it difficult at present to forecast outcomes for the people of Côte d’Ivoire.</p>
		</div>
		
